Let's write the testcase code:

public void testWithAsValueAndDefaultTyping() throws Exception {
    ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
    mapper.enableDefaultTyping(); // enable default typing
    ExternalTypeWithNonPOJO input = new ExternalTypeWithNonPOJO(new AsValueThingy(999L));
    String json = mapper.writeValueAsString(input);
    assertNotNull(json);
    // With default typing, the JSON will include type information.
    // We can just verify deserialization works.
    ExternalTypeWithNonPOJO result = mapper.readValue(json, ExternalTypeWithNonPOJO.class);
    assertNotNull(result);
    assertNotNull(result.value);
    assertEquals(AsValueThingy.class, result.value.getClass());
    assertEquals(999L, ((AsValueThingy) result.value).rawDate);
}

This test should fail on buggy code because type information may not be written correctly, causing deserialization to fail (maybe ClassCastException or missing type id). On fixed code, it should pass.

